 name\n! UK release date\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|| '' The Best of Crystal Maze''\n|| 16 May 1994\n|}\n\n==Transmissions==\n\n====Civilian====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Original series\n|-\n! Series\n! Start date \n! End date \n! Episodes \n! Presenter\n|-\n| '''1'''\n| 15 February 1990\n| 10 May 1990\n| rowspan=\"6\" |13\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Richard O'Brien]]\n|-\n| '''2'''\n| 21 March 1991\n| 13 June 1991\n|-\n| '''3'''\n| 23 April 1992\n| 16 July 1992 \n|-\n| '''4'''\n| 1 April 1993\n| 24 June 1993 \n|-\n| '''5'''\n| 12 May 1994\n| 4 August 1994\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Edward Tudor-Pole|Ed Tudor-Pole]]\n|-\n| '''6'''\n| 18 May 1995\n| 10 August 1995\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" |Revived series\n|-\n| '''1'''\n| 25 August 2017\n| 6 May 2018\n| 12<ref name=\"revival\"/>{{efn|name=Unaired|Production of the revived series 1 consisted of 15 episodes plus 5 celebrity specials, but thus far only 12 of the regular episodes have been broadcast in UK to date. There has been no official reason given for the withholding of the remaining three episodes, featuring 'The Ali Family', 'The Sasani Family and Friends' and 'The Midwives', they have however been broadcast in Australia on [[SBS Viceland]] and were available on the online streaming service [[SBS_(Australian_TV_channel)#SBS_On_Demand|SBS On Demand]].<ref name=\"unaired episodes\">{{cite web |date=30 May 2018 |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/1243486275861/the-crystal-maze-the-ali-family |title=The Crystal MazeSeason 1 Episode 13 \u2013 The Ali Family |publisher=[[SBS_(Australian_TV_channel)#SBS_On_Demand|SBS On Demand]] |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref>}} || rowspan=\"4\"| [[Richard Ayoade]]\n|-\n| '''2'''\n| 20 July 2018\n| 24 August 2018\n| 6<ref name=\"revival2\"/>\n|}\n\n====Christmas====\nFor the original run of the series, a Christmas special was filmed and featured younger contestants. In the revived series, a team of celebrities take part wherein the Maze has been given a Christmas aesthetic.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Date !! Presenter\n|-\n| 1 January 1991 || rowspan=\"3\" |[[Richard O'Brien]]\n|-\n| 24 December 1991 \n|-\n| 27 December 1992 \n|-\n| 24 December 1993 || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Edward Tudor-Pole|Ed Tudor-Pole]]\n|-\n| 24 December 1994 \n|-\n| 14 December 2017\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Richard Ayoade]]\n|-\n| 26 December 2018\n|-\n| 23 December 2019\n|}\n\n====Celebrity====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Series !! Start date !! End date !! Episodes !! Presenter\n|-\n| '''1''' || 23 June 2017 || 13 July 2017 || 4<ref name=\"revival\"/> || rowspan=\"3\"| [[Richard Ayoade]]\n|-\n| '''2''' || 8 June 2018 || 6 July 2018 || 5<ref name=\"revival2\"/> \n|-\n| '''3''' || 21 June 2019 || 26 July 2019 || 6\n|}\n\n====Stand Up to Cancer====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Presenter\n|-\n| 16 October 2016\n| [[Stephen Merchant]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==American version==\nOn June 3, 2019, it was announced that an American version of the show would premiere on [[Nickelodeon]] and feature family members competing for [[USD|$]]25,000.<ref name=\"Nickelodeon\"/> The ten-episode season was filmed in the same location as the British edition. In December 2019, it was announced that comedian [[Adam Conover]] would be the Maze Master of the version. It debuted with a [[Television advertisement|commercial-free]] premiere which aired on January 24, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/the-crystal-maze-names-adam-conover-host-nickelodeon-family-game-show-1202802945/|title=''The Crystal Maze'' Taps Adam Conover As Host Of New Nickelodeon Family Game Show|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Haring|first=Bruce|date=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nEach team plays a total of eight games in the maze (two per zone). The Mega Crystal introduced in 2019 in the original series is available in any game after the first. If a team finishes the Crystal Dome with a positive total of gold tokens, they win $100 per gold after deductions for silver tokens, and the full $25,000 for a net result of 100 gold tokens or more.\n\n====Episodes====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; margin:auto; background:#FFFFFF;\"\n|-style=\"color:#fff;\"\n!style=\"background-color:#191970;\"| Ep #\n!style=\"background-color:#191970;\"| Title\n!style=\"background-color:#191970;\"| Airdate\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 1\n |Title= The Walls Are Closing In!\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|01|24|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 2\n |Title= Swing It Like a Boss! \n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|01|31|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 3\n |Title= That's Gonna Leave a Mark\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|02|07|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 4\n |Title= The Foggy Abyss of Doom \n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|02|14|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 5\n |Title= What's The Sign for Winning?\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|02|21|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 6\n |Title= Keep Your Eyes On The Panda!\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|02|28|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 7\n |Title= I Can Read But I Can't Do That\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|03|06|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 8\n |Title= Show The Maze Who's Boss\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|03|13|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 9\n |Title= Space is a Difficult Place\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|03|20|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber= 10\n |Title= Put A Ring On It!\n |OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2020|03|27|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor= 191970\n}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Channel4.com|programmes/the-crystal-maze|The Crystal Maze}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0098774|title=The Crystal Maze}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-crystal-maze|The Crystal Maze}}\n* {{UKGameshow|The_Crystal_Maze}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crystal Maze, The}}\n[[Category:1990 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990s British game shows]]\n[[Category:2010s British game shows]]\n[[Category:British game shows]]\n[[Category:Channel 4 game shows]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by RDF Media Group]]\n[[Category:British television series revived after cancellation]]\n", "name_user": "Camwad83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Crystal_Maze"}
{"title_page": "Pyrrhus of Epirus", "text_new": "{{short description|King of Epirus}}\n{{About|the Epirote king|other uses|Pyrrhus (disambiguation){{!}}Pyrrhus}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type         = monarch\n| name         = Pyrrhus\n| image        = File:Pyrrhus MAN Napoli Inv6150 n03.jpg\n| image_size   = 250px\n| caption      = Bust of Pyrrhus at the [[National Archaeological Museum of Naples]]\n| succession   = [[King of Epirus]]\n| reign        = 297\u2013272 BC\n| predecessor  = [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]\n| successor    = [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]\n| reign1       = 306\u2013302 BC\n| predecessor1 = [[Alcetas II of Epirus|Alcetas II]]\n| successor1   = [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]\n| succession2  = [[List of ancient Macedonians|King of Macedonia]]\n| reign2       = 274\u2013272 BC\n| predecessor2 = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| successor2   = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| reign3       = 288\u2013285 BC\n| predecessor3 = [[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius I]]\n| successor3   = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| succession4  = [[List of tyrants of Syracuse|Tyrant of Syracuse]]\n| reign4       = 278\u2013276 BC\n| predecessor4 = [[:it:Tinione|Thinion]] & [[:it:Sosistrato di Agrigento|Sosistratus]]\n| successor4   = [[Hiero II of Syracuse|Hiero II]]\n| house        = [[Aeacidae]]\n| house-type   = Dynasty\n| spouse       = {{plain list|\n* [[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]]\n* [[Lanassa (wife of Pyrrhus)|Lanassa]]\n* [[Bircenna]]}}\n| issue        = {{plain list|\n* [[Olympias II of Epirus|Olympias]]\n* [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]]\n* [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]\n* Helenus\n}}\n| father       = [[Aeacides of Epirus|Aeacides]]\n| mother       = [[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]]\n| birth_date   = c. 319 BC\n| birth_place  = [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]], [[Ancient Greece|Greece]]\n| death_date   = 272 BC (aged about 46)\n| death_place  = [[Argos]], [[Peloponnese]], Greece\n| religion     = [[Greek mythology|Greek Paganism]]\n}}\n\n'''Pyrrhus''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u026ar|\u0259|s}}; {{lang-grc|\u03a0\u03cd\u03c1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Pyrrhos''; 319/318\u2013272 BC) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] king and [[wikt:statesman|statesman]] of the [[Hellenistic period]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hackens|1992|p=239}}; {{harvnb|Grant|2010|p=17}}; {{harvnb|Anglin|Hamblin|1993|p=121}}; {{harvnb|Richard|2003|p=139}}; {{harvnb|Sekunda|Northwood|Hook|1995|p=6}}; {{harvnb|Daly|2003|p=4}}; {{harvnb|Greene|2008|p=98}}; {{harvnb|Kishlansky|Geary|O'Brien|2005|p=113}}; {{harvnb|Saylor|2007|p=332}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1967|loc=pp. 340\u2013345}}; Hammond has argued convincingly that the Epirotes were a Greek-speaking people.</ref><ref name=\"Plutarch\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives'', \"[http://classics.mit.edu/Plutarch/pyrrhus.html Pyrrhus]\".</ref><ref name=BritB>{{harvnb|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|2013}}.</ref><ref name=BritA>{{harvnb|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Pyrrhus\")|2013}}.</ref> He was king of the [[List of ancient Greek tribes#Epirus|Greek]] tribe of [[Molossians]],<ref name=BritB/><ref>{{harvnb|Borza|1992|p=62}}.</ref> of the royal Aeacid house,<ref>{{harvnb|Jones|1999|p=45}}; {{harvnb|Chamoux|2003|p=62}}; {{harvnb|American Numismatic Society|1960|p=196}}.</ref> and later he became [[Monarch|king]] ([[John Malalas|Malalas]] also called him [[toparch]]<ref>[https://topostext.org/work/792#8.208 Malalas, Chronography, \u00a7 8.208 ]</ref>) of [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]]. He was one of the strongest opponents of early [[Roman Republic|Rome]]. Several of his victorious battles caused him unacceptably heavy losses, from which the term ''[[Pyrrhic victory]]'' was coined.\n\nPyrrhus became king of Epirus in 306 BC at the age of 13, but was dethroned by [[Cassander]] four years later. He saw action during the [[Wars of the Diadochi]] and regained his throne in 297 BC with the support of [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. During what came to be known as the [[Pyrrhic War]], Pyrrhus fought Rome at the behest of [[Taranto|Tarentum]], scoring costly victories at [[Battle of Heraclea|Heraclea]] and [[Battle of Asculum|Asculum]]. He proceeded to take over [[Sicily]] from [[Carthage]] but was soon driven out, and lost all his gains in Italy after the [[Battle of Beneventum (275 BC)|Battle of Beneventum]] in 275 BC.\n\nPyrrhus seized the Macedonian throne from [[Antigonus II Gonatas]] in 274 BC and [[Pyrrhus' invasion of the Peloponnese|invaded the Peloponnese]] in 272 BC. The Epirote [[Siege of Sparta|assault on Sparta]] was thwarted, however, and Pyrrhus was killed during a street battle at [[Argos]].\n\n==Early life==\nIn c. 319 BC, Pyrrhus was born to prince [[Aeacides of Epirus|Aeacides]] of Epirus,<ref>At Pyrrhus' birth in 319 BC, Aeacides was only a prince and his father, Arrybas, ruled Epirus as a regent to the underaged King Neoptolemus.</ref> and [[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]], a Thessalian noblewoman, the daughter of the Thessalian general [[Menon IV of Pharsalus|Menon]]. Aeacides was a cousin of [[Olympias]], making Pyrrhus a second-cousin-once-removed to [[Alexander the Great]]. He had two sisters: [[Deidamia I of Epirus|Deidamia]] and Troias. In 319/318 BC, Arrybas, Aeacides' father and the regent of Epirus, died leaving Epirus to the joint kings Aeacides and [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus]]. \n\nAeacides supported Olympias in her fight against [[Cassander]] and marched on Macedon. In 317 BC, when Pyrrhus was only two, Olympias requested Aeacides' support yet again and he marched on Macedon a second time. Many of his soldiers did not like their service and mutinied. Aeacides released these soldiers from his army, but as a result his army was too small to achieve anything. When the mutineers arrived in Epirus they caused a rebellion against their absent king and Aeacides was dethroned. Cassander sent one of his generals, Lyciscus, to act as regent to the still underaged Neoptolemus. Epirus in effect became a puppet kingdom of Cassander. Pyrrhus' family fled north and took refuge with [[King Glaukias|Glaukias]] of the [[Taulantii|Taulantians]], one of the largest [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tribes.<ref name=BritA/> Pyrrhus was raised by [[Beroea of Epirus|Beroea]], Glaukias' wife, a [[Molossian]] of the [[Aeacidae]] dynasty.<ref name=\"Plutarch\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1992|p=124}}.</ref> Cassander marched against Glaukias, defeated his army and captured [[Apollonia (Illyria)|Apollonia]]. Glaukias had to promise not to act against Cassander, but he refused to give up Pyrrhus and his family.<ref name=JFP12>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=12}}.</ref>\n\nBy 313 BC, Cassander was distracted by his war against [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus|Antigonus Monophthalmus]], one of the most powerful of the [[Diadochi]]. Fearing an invasion from [[Asia Minor]], where Antigonus was building up his forces, he shifted his attention from west to the east. Aeacides took advantage of the situation and returned to Epirus. He appears to have regained popularity and raised a large army. Cassander sent an army under his brother Philip who defeated Aeacides in two battles. Aeacides was wounded in the last battle and died soon after.<ref name=JFP12/>\n\n==First reign==\nIn 307 BC, Glaukias invaded Epirus and put Pyrrhus upon the throne. Pyrrhus was only eleven years old, his guardians would rule in his stead until he came of age.<ref>Justin, ''Epitome'', 17.3.</ref> When he was seventeen he travelled to the court of Glaukias to attend the wedding of one of Glaukias' sons, while he was in Illyria the [[Molossians]] rose in rebellion and drove out Pyrrhus' supporters and placed Neoptolemus back on the throne. This time Glaukias was unable to help him.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=14}}; Glaukias' kingdom was being attacked by pirates.</ref> \n\n==Exile==\nPyrrhus travelled to the [[Peloponnese]] and served his brother-in-law [[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius Poliorcetes]] who had married his sister Deidamia, and who was campaigning against Cassander in southern Greece.\n\n===The Battle of Ipsus===\n{{main|Battle of Ipsus}}\nIn 302 BC, Demetrius took his army to Asia Minor to support his father Antigonus Monophthalmus. Pyrrhus impressed Antigonus for he is reputed to have said that Pyrrhus would become the greatest general of his time, if he lived long enough.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=15}}.</ref>\n\nAntigonus had grown too powerful and the other successors, [[Seleucus I Nicator|Seleucus]], [[Lysimachus]], [[Ptolemy I Soter|Ptolemy]] and [[Cassander]], had united against him. Lysimachus and Seleucus, reinforced by two of Cassander's armies, had concentrated their forces in Asia Minor and marched on Antigonus. Both armies met at [[Ipsus]] in [[Phrygia]]. The Battle of Ipsus was the largest and most important battle of the [[Wars of the Diadochi|Wars of the Successors]]. Pyrrhus probably fought with Demetrius on the right wing, a place of honour, and made a brilliant display of valour among the combatants. Unfortunately for Antigonus, he lost both the battle and his life. Demetrius, victorious on his wing, managed to escape with 9,000 men. Pyrrhus, still with Demetrius, continued to serve his brother-in-law who started rebuilding his father's empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=14\u201317}}.</ref>\n\n===Ptolemy===\nIn 298 BC, Pyrrhus was taken hostage to Alexandria, under the terms of a peace treaty made between Demetrius and [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. There, he married Ptolemy I's stepdaughter [[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]] (a daughter of [[Berenice I of Egypt]] from her first husband [[Philip (first husband of Berenice I of Egypt)|Philip]]\u2014respectively, Ptolemy I's wife and a Macedonian noble). In 297 BC, Cassander died and Ptolemy, always looking for allies, decided to help restore Pyrrhus to his kingdom. He provided Pyrrhus with men and funds and sent him back to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=18}}.</ref>\n\n==Second reign==\nPyrrhus returned to Epirus at the head of an army, but not willing to fight a civil war he agreed to rule Epirus together with Neoptolemus. Soon both kings started to plot against one another. Pyrrhus was informed of a plot against his life and decided to strike first. He invited his fellow king to a dinner and had him murdered. The act does not appear to be unpopular as Epirus' nobility seem to have been devoted to him.<ref>Plutarch. ''Life of Pyrrhus'', 5.</ref> \n\nIn 295 BC, Pyrrhus transferred the capital of his kingdom to [[Arta, Greece|Ambracia]]. In 292 BC, he went to war against his former ally and brother-in-law Demetrius, he invaded [[Thessaly]] while Demetrius was [[Siege of Thebes (292-291 BC)|besieging Thebes]]. Demetrius responded immediately, he left the siege to his son [[Antigonus Gonatas]] and marched back north at the head of a large army.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=32}}; Demetrius commanded the full might of the Macedonian army which at that particular time was much larger than the army of Epirus.</ref> Pyrrhus, outnumbered, withdrew to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=32}}.</ref>\n\nWhile he was back in Epirus, Pyrrhus suffered another setback. His second wife Lannasa, daughter of [[Agathocles of Syracuse|Agathocles]] the self proclaimed king of [[Sicily]], deserted him. She claimed that she, a daughter of a Greek king, could no longer bear to share her home with barbarian women. She fled to [[Corcyra]], her dowry, and offered it and herself to Demetrius. He accepted, sailed to the island and took possession of both Corcyra and Lannasa. After returning to his army in mainland Greece, Demetrius planned to invade Epirus. In 289 BC, he invaded Pyrrhus' allies the [[Aetolian League|Aetolians]], hoping to neutralize them before he invaded Epirus. The Aetolians refused battle and retreated into the hills. After ransacking their countryside, Demetrius left a strong force under his best general Pantauchus in Aetolia and marched on Epirus. Meanwhile, Pyrrhus had raised his army and was marching to his allies rescue. The two armies, on different roads, passed one another and Demetrius started plundering Epirus while Pyrrhus met Pantauchus in battle.\n\nPyrrhus had the bulk of the army of Epirus with him, probably 20,000-25,000 men, while Pantauchus commanded but a detachment of Demetrius' army consisting of around 11,000 men. The fighting was heavy, and according to the sources Pantauchus and Pyrrhus sought out one another. Pantauchus challenged Pyrrhus to individual combat, Pyrrhus accepted. After hurling spears at each other they fought it out with swords. Pyrrhus was wounded, but in return wounded his opponent twice, in the thigh and in the neck. Pantauchus' bodyguards had to carry him away. Emboldened by their king's victory the Epirots resumed their attack and broke Pantauchus' army, and took 5,000 prisoners. The army then honoured Pyrrhus by bestowing the surname of 'Eagle' upon him. Demetrius, upon hearing of Pyrrhus' victory, marched back to Macedon. Pyrrhus released his prisoners and marched back to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=33\u201334}}.</ref>\n \nIn 289 BC, Pyrrhus, learning that Demetrius was dangerously ill, invaded Macedonia. His original intention was merely to raid and pillage, but with Demetrius unable to lead his forces he met almost no opposition. Pyrrhus penetrated as far as the old Macedonian capital of Aegae before Demetrius was well enough to take the field. Since Demetrius commanded a superior force Pyrrhus had no choice but to retreat.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=34}}.</ref>\n\nDemetrius, just as restless as Pyrrhus, planned to invade Asia and reclaim his father's old domains. He first made peace with Pyrrhus granting him his holdings in Macedonia while holding on to Corcyra and Leucas, then he started to raise a vast army and a huge fleet.<ref>Reputedly raising 110,000 soldiers and 500 ships.</ref> Faced with this threat, the other Diadochi, Lysimachus, Ptolemy and Seleucus, allied against him. The three kings sent embassies to Pyrrhus trying to win him over to their side or at least get him to remain neutral. If the allies won and Pyrrhus remained neutral he would gain nothing. If on the other hand Demetrius would be victorious he could overwhelm Pyrrhus at any time in the future. Pyrrhus personal enmity against Demetrius might have played an additional role in his decision to join the allies.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=34\u201335}}.</ref>\n\nIn 288 BC, the allied kings began their campaigns against Demetrius. Ptolemy sailed against Demetrius' Greek allies with a large fleet. Lysimachus invaded upper Macedonia from Thrace. Pyrrhus waited untill Demetrius had marched against Lysimachus and then invaded southern Macedonia. Demetrius must have thought Pyrrhus would not renege on his treaty for western and southern Macedonia fell without opposition. Meanwhile, Demetrius had won a victory over Lysimachus near [[Amphipolis]]. When the Macedonian army heard their homeland was being overrun by Pyrrhus they turned on Demetrius. They were fed up with his autocratic rule and grandiose plans and refused to advance any further. Demetrius then led his army against Pyrrhus, probably hoping his Macedonians would be more willing to fight a foreign invader than Lysimachus, a veteran of Alexander. Unfortunately for Demetrius, his troops were so fed up with him they deserted to Pyrrhus and he had to flee. Lysimachus was soon joined by Pyrrhus and they decided to share rulership over Macedonia.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=35\u201336}}.</ref>\n\nDemetrius gathered a new army in Greece and besieged Athens, which had rebelled against the puppet government he had installed. The Athenians called on Pyrrhus for assistance and he marched against Demetrius once more. This caused Demetrius to raise the siege. The Athenians thanked Pyrrhus, they erected a bust to him and allowed him into the city for the celebrations. However, they did not allow his army to enter the city, probably fearing Pyrrhus would install a garrison and make himself overlord of Athens. Pyrrhus made the most of the situation and advised the Athenians never to let a king enter their city again.<ref name=JFP37>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=37}}.</ref>\n\nPyrrhus and Demetrius made peace once more but, like all previous agreements, it did not last. When Demetrius, in 286 BC, invaded Asia, to attack Lysimachus' Asian domains, Lysimachus requested Pyrrhus invade Thessaly and from there attack Demetrius' garrisons in Greece. Pyrrhus agreed, probably to keep his fractious Macedonian troops busy and less likely to rebel and also to gain an easy victory over the weakened Antigonids.<ref>Plutarch. ''Pyrrhus'', 12; Plutarch. ''Demetrius'', 41.</ref> He quickly defeated [[Antigonus Gonatas]], Demetrius' son, who ceded Thessaly to him in order to make peace. Pyrrhus' Greek Empire was now at its zenith, he ruled an enlarged Epirus, half of Macedonia and Thessaly.<ref name=JFP37/> \n\nIn 285 BC, Demetrius was defeated by Seleucus. This freed the hands of Lysimachus who decided to get rid of his co-ruler in Macedonia. He first isolated Pyrrhus from his traditional ally the Ptolemies, by marrying [[Arsinoe II|Arsinoe]], the sister of [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus|Ptolemy II]]. He also made a large donation to the [[Aetolians]], Pyrrhus' main allies in Greece. Pyrrhus felt threatened enough to make an alliance with Antigonus Gonatas. In 284 BC, Lysimachus invaded Pyrrhus' half of Macedonia with a huge army.<ref>In 301 BC, at the Battle of Ipsus, Lysimachus had fielded 40,000 troops. Since then he had acquired half of Macedonia and western Asia Minor. With these combined assets his army could have numbered over 70,000 troops. Pyrrhus commanded 40,000 troops at best.</ref> Unable to stand against Lysimachus' superior army Pyrrhus retreated and linked up with Antigonus Gonatas. Lysimachus started a propaganda campaign in which he appealed to the patriotism of the Macedonians serving Pyrrhus. He reminded them that Pyrrhus was in fact a foreign king while he himself was a true Macedonian. The campaign was successful. With his Macedonian troops turning against him Pyrrhus had no other choice but to withdraw to Epirus. Lysimachus invaded an plundered Epirus the following year. Pyrrhus did not oppose Lysimachus for he was probably fighting a war in Illyria to the north. According to Pausanius, \"Pyrrhus was roaming around as usual\".<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=37\u201339}}; {{harvnb|Greenwalt|2010|p=298: \"From 288 until 284, Pyrrhus and Lysimachus shared the rule of Macedonia until the latter drove the former back to Epirus (Plut., ''Pyrrhus'' 7\u201312).\"}}; Pausanius. ''Guide to Greece'', 1.7.</ref>\n\n==Struggle with Rome==\n{{Main|Pyrrhic War|}}\n[[Image:Pyrrhic War Italy en.svg|thumb|left|Routes taken against Rome in the [[Pyrrhic War]] (280\u2013275 BC).]]\n[[Image:Map of ancient Epirus and environs (English).svg|thumb|Tribes of Epirus in antiquity.]]\n[[File:Pyrrhus and his Elephants.gif|thumb|upright|Pyrrhus and his elephants.]]\n\nThe Greek city of [[Taranto|Tarentum]], in [[Mezzogiorno|southern Italy]], fell out with [[Roman Republic|Rome]] due to a violation of an old treaty that specified Rome was not to send warships into the [[Tarentine Gulf]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hackens|1992|loc=pp. 20-21: \"When, however, a Roman fleet sailed into the Tarentine Gulf (perhaps in order to place a garrison in Thurii) and thereby violated the terms of a treaty probably made at the time of Cleomynus, Tarentum responded swiftly \u2026 \"}}</ref> In 282 BC, the Romans installed garrisons in the Greek cities of [[Thurii]] (on the western end of the Tarentine Gulf), [[Locri]], and [[Rhegium]], and sent warships to Thurii. Although this was designed as a measure against the Italian peoples of [[Lucanians|Lucania]], the Tarentines grew nervous and attacked the Romans in Thurii, driving the Roman garrison from the city and sinking several Roman warships. Tarentum was now faced with a Roman attack and certain defeat, unless they could enlist the aid of greater powers. Rome had already made itself into a major power, and was poised to subdue all the Greek cities in [[Magna Graecia]]. The Tarentines asked Pyrrhus to lead their war against the Romans.<ref name=BritA/><ref name=encarta2008>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Pyrrhus|encyclopedia=Encarta|publisher=Microsoft Corporation|year=2008}}</ref> Pyrrhus was encouraged to aid the Tarentines by the [[Oracle of Delphi]]. He recognized the possibility of carving out an empire for himself in [[Italy]]. He made an alliance with [[Ptolemy Keraunos]], King of [[Macedon]] and his most powerful neighbor, and arrived in Italy in 280 BC.\n\nPyrrhus entered Italy with an army consisting of 20,000 [[infantry]], 3,000 [[cavalry]], 2,000 [[archery|archers]], 500 [[sling (weapon)|slingers]], and 20 [[war elephant]]s in a bid to subdue the Romans.<ref name=BritA/> The elephants had been loaned to him by [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus]], who had also promised 9,000 soldiers and a further 50 elephants to defend Epirus while Pyrrhus and his army were away.\n\nDue to his superior cavalry, his elephants and his deadly [[macedonian phalanx|phalanx infantry]], he defeated the Romans, led by [[Consul]] [[Publius Valerius Laevinus]], in the [[Battle of Heraclea]] in 280 BC,<ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/History-of-Liberty-the-Ancient-Romans-Volume-2/105987/37 \"History of Liberty: The Ancient Romans\" (1853), p. 6.]</ref> in the Roman province of [[Lucania]]. There are conflicting sources about casualties. [[Hieronymus of Cardia]] reports the Romans lost about 7,000 while Pyrrhus lost 3,000 soldiers, including many of his best; Dionysius gives a bloodier view of 15,000 Roman dead and 13,000 Epirot.<ref name=\"Plutarch17.4\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0060%3Achapter%3D17%3Asection%3D4 17.4].</ref> Several tribes, including the [[Lucanians]], [[Bruttii]], [[Messapians]], and the Greek cities of [[Crotone|Croton]] and [[Locri]], joined Pyrrhus. He then offered the Romans a peace treaty which was eventually rejected. Pyrrhus tried to wrest [[Campania]] from the Romans, but was twarted in this by the reinforced army of Laevinus. He then boldly marched on Rome itself, but found its defences too formidable. Meanwhile, the Romans had made peace with the Etruscans and had recalled [[Tiberius Coruncanius]], the other consul, who was marching his army southwards from [[Etruria]] towards Rome. Pyrrhus now faced three armies; the garrison of Rome, Laevinus from the south and Curuncanius from the north. Not wanting to be caught between three armies Pyrrhus withdrew to Tarentum, where he wintered his troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=75\u201376}}.</ref>\n\nWhen Pyrrhus invaded [[Apulia]] (279 BC), the two armies met in the [[Battle of Asculum]], where Pyrrhus won a costly victory.<ref name=encarta2008/> The consul [[Publius Decius Mus (279 BC)|Publius Decius Mus]] was the Roman commander, and while his able force was ultimately defeated, they almost managed to break the back of Pyrrhus' Epirot army, which guaranteed the security of the city itself. In the end, the Romans lost 6,000 men and Pyrrhus 3,500 including many officers.<ref name=BritA/> Pyrrhus later famously commented on his victory at Asculum, stating, \"If we are victorious in one more battle with the Romans, we shall be utterly ruined\".<ref name=\"Plutarch21.9\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Pyrrhus*.html#21 21.9].</ref> It is from reports of this semi-legendary event that the term [[Pyrrhic victory]] originates.\n\n==Ruler of Sicily==\nIn 278 BC, Pyrrhus received two offers simultaneously. The Greek cities in [[Sicily]] asked him to come and drive out [[Carthage]], which along with Rome was one of the two great powers of the Western [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. At the same time, the [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonians]], whose King [[Ptolemy Keraunos]] had been killed by invading [[Gauls]], asked Pyrrhus to ascend the throne of Macedon. Pyrrhus decided that Sicily offered him a greater opportunity, and transferred his army there.<ref name=BritA/>\n\nSoon after landing in Sicily, he lifted the Carthaginian [[Siege of Syracuse (278 BC)|siege of Syracuse]] in the same year. Pyrrhus was proclaimed king of Sicily. He was already making plans for his son Helenus to inherit the kingdom of Sicily and his other son Alexander to be given Italy. In 277 BC, Pyrrhus captured [[Eryx (Sicily)|Eryx]], the strongest Carthaginian fortress in Sicily. This prompted the rest of the Carthaginian-controlled cities to defect to Pyrrhus.\n\nIn 276 BC, Pyrrhus negotiated with the Carthaginians. Although they were inclined to come to terms with Pyrrhus, supply him money and send him ships once friendly relations were established, he demanded that Carthage abandon all of Sicily and make the Libyan Sea a boundary between themselves and the Greeks. The Greek cities of Sicily opposed making peace with Carthage because the Carthaginians still controlled the powerful fortress of [[Lilybaeum]], on the western end of the island. Pyrrhus eventually gave in to their proposals and broke off the peace negotiations. Pyrrhus' army then began [[Siege of Lilybaeum|besieging Lilybaeum]]. For two months he launched unsuccessful assaults on the city, until finally he realized he could not mount an effective siege without blockading it from the sea as well. Pyrrhus then requested manpower and money from the Sicilians in order to construct a powerful fleet. When the Sicilians became unhappy about these contributions he had to resort to compulsory contributions and force to keep them in line. These measures culminated in him proclaiming a military dictatorship of Sicily and installing military garrisons in Sicilian cities.<ref>{{harvnb|Garouphalias|1979|pp=97\u2013108}}.</ref>\n\nThese actions were deeply unpopular and soon Sicilian opinion became inflamed against him. Pyrrhus had so alienated the Sicilian Greeks that they were willing to make common cause with the Carthaginians. The Carthaginians took heart from this and sent another army against him. This army was promptly defeated. In spite of this victory, Sicily continued to grow increasingly hostile to Pyrrhus, who began to consider abandoning Sicily. At this point, Samnite and Tarentine envoys reached Pyrrhus and informed him that of all the Greek cities in Italy, only Tarentum had not been conquered by Rome. Pyrrhus made his decision and departed from Sicily. As his ship left the island, he turned and, foreshadowing the [[Punic Wars]], said to his companions: \"What a wrestling ground we are leaving, my friends, for the Carthaginians and the Romans.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Garouphalias|1979|pp=109\u2013112}}.</ref><ref>Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0060%3Achapter%3D23%3Asection%3D6 23.6].</ref> While his army was being transported by ship to mainland Italy, Pyrrhus' navy was destroyed by the Carthaginians at the [[Battle of the Strait of Messina]], with 98 warships sunk or disabled out of 110.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"105px\">\nFile:Pyros.jpg|Coin of Pyrrhus minted at [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], 278 BC. Obverse: Veiled head of [[Phthia of Epirus|Phtia]] with oak wreath, caption \u03a6\u0398\u0399\u0391\u03a3 (of Phtia). Reverse: [[Thunderbolt]], \u0392\u0391\u03a3\u0399\u039b\u0395\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0\u03a5\u03a1\u03a1\u039f\u03a5 (of King Pyrrhus).\nFile:Pyrrhos KING of EPEIROS 297 272 BC.jpg|Pyrrhos, King of Epeiros, 297\u201372 BC. Head of Zeus in wreath of oak / Demeter seated, holding long sceptre and her veil; caption \u0392\u0391\u03a3\u0399\u039b\u0395\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0\u03a5\u03a1\u03a1\u039f\u03a5 (of king Pyrrhus).\nFile:Pyrrhus Kingdom of Epirus.JPG|Coin of Pyrrhus, [[Epirus (ancient state)|Kingdom of Epirus]] Head of Kore left, wreathed with grain, long torch behind / Athena Alkis advancing left, brandishing spear in right hand & holding shield on left arm, star before face, thunderbolt in left field, E in right field; inscription BA\u03a3I\u039bE\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0Y\u03a1\u03a1OY (of King Pyrrhus).\n</gallery>\n\n==Retreat from Italy==\nWhile Pyrrhus had been campaigning against the Carthaginians, the Romans had rebuilt their army by calling up thousands of fresh [[Army recruit|recruits]]. When Pyrrhus returned from Sicily, he found himself vastly outnumbered against a superior Roman army under [[Manius Curius Dentatus]]. After the inconclusive [[Battle of Beneventum (275 BC)|Battle of Beneventum]] in 275 BC, Pyrrhus decided to end his campaign in Italy and return to Epirus which resulted in the loss of essentially all the gains he had made in Italy. The city of Tarentum remained under the dominion of the Epirotes.\n\n==Last wars and death==\n{{Main|Siege of Sparta|}}\n[[File:The-Siege-Of-Sparta-By-Pyrrhus-319-272-Bc-1799-1800.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Siege of Sparta]], by [[Fran\u00e7ois Topino-Lebrun]]]]\n\nHis western campaign had taken a heavy toll on his army as well as his treasury. Despite (or perhaps because of) this, Pyrrhus went to war yet again.<ref>The easiest way for a king to raise funds was to invade his neighbours.</ref> The realm of his rival king [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus Gonatas]] of Macedon was the most obvious target. Pyrrhus raised an army from his Epirote garrisons, Gallic mercenaries and the troops he had brought back from Italy and marched east into Macedon. He won an easy victory at the [[Battle of the Aous (274 BC)|Battle of the Aous]] and took most of Macedon.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=125\u2013128}}; Plutarch. ''Life of Pyrrhus'', 26.</ref>\n\nAntigonus managed to hold on to a number of coastal cities.<ref>He had inherited a powerful navy from his father, Demetrius.</ref> He then waited for an opportunity to reclaim his kingdom while Pyrrhus was already looking for another war to fight. Furthermore Pyrrhus made himself very unpopular in Macedon by allowing his Gauls to plunder the tombs of the Macedonian kings at Aegae.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=128}}.</ref> \n\nIn 272 BC, [[Cleonymus of Sparta|Cleonymus]], a [[Sparta]]n of royal blood who was hated among fellow Spartans, asked Pyrrhus to attack Sparta and place him in power. Pyrrhus agreed to the plan, intending to win control of the [[Peloponnese]] for himself, but unexpected strong resistance thwarted his [[Siege of Sparta|assault on Sparta]]. On the retreat he lost his firstborn son [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]], who had been in command of the rearguard.\n\nPyrrhus had little time to mourn, as he was immediately offered an opportunity to intervene in a civic dispute in [[Pyrrhus'_invasion_of_the_Peloponnese#Battle_of_Argos|Argos]]. Since Antigonus Gonatas was approaching too, he hastened to enter the city with his army by stealth, only to find the place crowded with hostile troops. During the confused [[Battle of Argos]] in the narrow city streets, Pyrrhus was trapped.  While he was fighting an Argive soldier, the soldier's old mother, who was watching from a rooftop, threw a tile which knocked him from his horse and broke part of his spine, paralyzing him.  Whether he was alive or not after the blow is unknown, but his death was assured when a Macedonian soldier named Zopyrus, though frightened by the look on the face of the unconscious king, hesitantly and ineptly beheaded his motionless body. This story is later recounted by Plutarch in his ''Life of Pyrrhus.'' \n\nAntigonus had him cremated with all honours and sent his surviving son Helenus back to Epirus. That same year, upon hearing the news of Pyrrhus's death, the Tarentinians surrendered to Rome.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:20140415 ioannina524.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|A statue of Pyrrhus in [[Ioannina]], [[Greece]].]]\n\nIn his ''Life of Pyrrhus'', [[Plutarch]] records that [[Hannibal]] ranked him as the greatest commander the world had ever seen,<ref name = \"Plutarch\"/> though in the ''Life of Titus Quinctius Flamininus'', Plutarch writes that Hannibal placed him second after [[Alexander the Great]]. This latter account is also given by [[Appian]].<ref name=\"Appian\">Appian. ''History of the Syrian Wars'', [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_syriaca_02.html \u00a710] and [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_syriaca_03.html \u00a711].</ref> While he was a mercurial and often restless leader, and not always a wise king, he was considered one of the greatest military commanders of his time. \n\nPyrrhus was known for his benevolence. As a general, Pyrrhus's greatest political weaknesses were his failures to maintain focus and to maintain a strong treasury at home (many of his soldiers were costly mercenaries). \n\nHis name is famous for the term \"[[Pyrrhic victory]]\" which refers to an exchange at the Battle of Asculum. In response to congratulations for winning a costly victory over the Romans, he is reported to have said: \"If we are victorious in one more battle with the Romans, we shall be utterly ruined\".<ref name=\"Plutarch21.9\" />\n\nPyrrhus and his campaign in Italy was effectively the only chance for Greece to check the advance of Rome towards domination of the Mediterranean world. Rather than banding together, the various Hellenistic powers continued to quarrel among themselves, sapping the financial and military strength of Greece and to a lesser extent, Macedon and the greater Hellenistic world. By 197 BC, Macedonia and many southern Greek city-states became Roman client states; in 188 BC, the [[Seleucid Empire]] was forced to cede most of [[Asia Minor]] to Rome's ally [[Pergamon]] (Pergamum). Rome inherited that state, and most of Asia Minor in 133 BC. Total Roman domination over Greece proper was marked by the [[Battle of Corinth (146 BC)|destruction of Corinth]] in 146 BC; Greece then formed an integral part of the Roman world leading into the [[Byzantine]] period.\n\nPyrrhus wrote memoirs and several books on the art of war. These have since been lost, although, according to Plutarch, Hannibal was influenced by them,<ref name=\"Plutarch\"/> and they received praise from [[Cicero]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tinsley|2006|p=211}}.</ref>\n\nPyrrhus was married five times: his first wife Antigone bore him a daughter called [[Olympias II of Epirus|Olympias]] and a son named [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]] in honour of her [[Ptolemy I Soter|stepfather]]. She died in 295 BC, possibly in childbirth, since that was the same year her son was born.<ref name=\"harvnb|Bennett|2010\">{{harvnb|Bennett|2010}}.</ref> His second wife was [[Lanassa (wife of Pyrrhus)|Lanassa]], daughter of King [[Agathocles of Syracuse]] (r. 317\u2013289 BC), whom he married in about 295 BC; the couple had two sons, [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander]]<ref name=\"harvnb|Bennett|2010\"/> and Helenus; Lanassa left Pyrrhus. His third wife was the daughter of [[Audoleon]], King of [[Paeonia (kingdom)|Paeonia]]; his fourth wife was the Illyrian princess [[Bircenna]], who was the daughter of King [[Bardylis II]] (r. c. 295\u2013290 BC); and his fifth wife was the daughter of [[Ptolemy Keraunos]], whom he married in 281/280 BC. Portraits of Pyrrhus as have come down to us do not necessarily reflect his likeness.<ref>{{harvnb|Winkes|1995|pp=175\u2013188}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=American Numismatic Society|title=Numismatic Literature, Issues 50-57|publisher=American Numismatic Society|year=1960|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZGkvAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Anglin|first1=Jay Pascal|last2=Hamblin|first2=William James|title=HarperCollins College Outline World History to 1648|location=New York, NY|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993|isbn=0-06-467123-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t4luVpw3NOIC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Chris|title=Antigone (Egyptian Royal Genealogy - The Ptolemaic Dynasty)|publisher=Tyndale House|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/egypt/ptolemies/antigone_fr.htm|year=2010|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Borza|first=Eugene N.|title=In the Shadow of Olympus: The Emergence of Macedon (Revised Edition)|location=Princeton, NJ|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1992|isbn=0-691-00880-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=614pd07OtfQC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Champion|first=Jeff|title=Pyrrhus of Epirus|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire|publisher=Pen & Sword Books Limited|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84468-282-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6YivDwAAQBAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Chamoux|first=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Hellenistic Civilization|location=Oxford, UK|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|year=2003|isbn=0-631-22242-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nafU9ADpCwcC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Daly|first=Gregory|title=Cannae: The Experience of Battle in the Second Punic War|location=New York, NY and London, UK|publisher=Routledge (Taylor & Francis)|year=2003|isbn=0-203-98750-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XzkY6voGtHgC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/190156/Epirus|title=Epirus|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|year=2013|accessdate=1 July 2013|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Pyrrhus\")|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/485118/Pyrrhus|title=Pyrrhus|year=2013|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|accessdate=1 July 2013|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Garouphalias|first=Petros|title=Pyrrhus: King of Epirus|location=London, UK|publisher=Stacey International|year=1979|isbn=0-905743-13-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d2cJAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=R. G.|title=Commanders: History's Greatest Military Leaders|location=New York, NY|publisher=DK Publishing|year=2010|isbn=0-7566-7341-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tFQcwH2StsMC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Greene|first=Robert|title=The 33 Strategies of War|location=London, UK|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|year=2008|isbn=0-14-311278-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l3GD2EgazCkC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Greenwalt|first=William S.|chapter=Macedonia, Illyria, and Epirus|title=A Companion to Ancient Macedonia|pages=279\u2013305|location=Oxford, Chichester, & Malden|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4051-7936-2|url=https://archive.org/stream/AncientMacedonia/Ancient%20Macedonia#page/n401/mode/2up|editor-given1=Joseph|editor-surname1=Roisman|editor-given2=Ian|editor-surname2=Worthington|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Hackens|editor-first=Tony|title=The Age of Pyrrhus: Papers Delivered at the International Conference, Brown University, 8\u201310 April, 1988 (Archaeologia Transatlantica XI)|location=Providence, RI|publisher=Center for Old World Archaeology and Art, Brown University|year=1992|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NIsiAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Epirus: The Geography, the Ancient Remains, the History and the Topography of Epirus and Adjacent Areas|location=Oxford|publisher=The Clarendon Press|year=1967|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xmKSQgAACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jones|first=Christopher Prestige|title=Kinship Diplomacy in the Ancient World|location=Cambridge, MA|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1999|isbn=0-674-50527-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zDm7315nUk0C|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Kishlansky|first1=Mark A.|last2=Geary|first2=Patrick|last3=O'Brien|first3=Patricia|title=Civilization in the West (Volume 1, Parts 1-12)|location=London, UK|publisher=Pearson Longman|year=2005|isbn=0-321-23621-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9xKUDDmbp18C|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Richard|first=Carl J.|title=Twelve Greeks and Romans who Changed the World|location=Oxford, UK|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield Publishers, Incorporated|year=2003|isbn=0-7425-2791-3|url=https://archive.org/details/twelvegreeksroma00carl|url-access=registration|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Saylor|first=Steven|title=Roma: The Novel of Ancient Rome|location=New York, NY|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2007|isbn=0-312-32831-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bp58sxv6JJkC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sekunda|first1=Nick|last2=Northwood|first2=Simon|last3=Hook|first3=Richard|title=Early Roman Armies|location=Oxford, UK|publisher=Osprey Publishing|year=1995|isbn=1-85532-513-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlO_YS_UilYC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tinsley|first=Barbara Sher|title=Reconstructing Western Civilization: Irreverent Essays on Antiquity|location=Selingsgrove, PA|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|year=2006|isbn=1-57591-095-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xwrC2CC_QBsC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winkes|first=John|title=The Illyrians|location=Oxford, UK|publisher=Blackwell Publishers Limited|year=1995|origyear=1992|isbn=0-631-19807-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Nv6SPRKqs8C|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=Rolf|chapter=The Pyrrhus Portrait|editor-last=Hackens|editor-first=Tony|title=The Age of Pyrrhus, Proceedings of an International Conference held at Brown University April 8\u201310, 1988 (Archaeologia Transatlantica XI)|year=1992|location=Providence, RI|publisher=Center for Old World Archaeology and Art, Brown University|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=eiKBU-CWKo-3sATTtYG4CA&id=NIsiAQAAIAAJ|pages=175\u2013188|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Abbott|first=Jacob|title=Makers of History: Pyrrhus|year=1901|location=New York and London|publisher=Harper & Brothers Publishers|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/27240}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cowan|first=Ross|title=Roman Conquests: Italy|year=2009|location=Barnsley|publisher=Pen & Sword Books Limited|isbn=978-1-84-415937-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sENvPgAACAAJ|pages=103\u2013147}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cowan|first=Ross|title=For the Glory of Rome: A History of Warriors and Warfare|year=2007|location=London|publisher=Greenhill Books|isbn=978-1-85-367733-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZR_GNJjJioC|pages=15\u201377}}\n* {{cite book|last=Franke|first=P. R.|chapter=CHAPTER 10 PYRRHUS|pages=456\u2013485|editor-last1=Astin|editor-first1=A. E.|editor-last2=Walbank|editor-first2=F. W.|editor-last3=Frederiksen|editor-first3=M. W.|editor-last4=Ogilvie|editor-first4=R. M.|editor-last5=Drummond|editor-first5=A.|title=The Cambridge Ancient History: The Rise of Rome to 220 BC|volume=VII, Part 2|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1989|isbn=0-521-23446-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3qXuay2SEtIC|ref=harv}}\n\n* {{cite book|last=Leveque|first=Pierre|title=Pyrrhos|year=1957|location=Paris|publisher=E. de Boccard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5SeGAAAAIAAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.livius.org/articles/person/pyrrhus-of-epirus/ Pyrrhus of Epirus on Livius.org]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Pyrrhus|short=x}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[King of Epirus]]|before=[[Alcetas II of Epirus|Alcetas II]]|after=[[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]|years=307\u2013302 BC}}\n{{succession box|title=[[King of Epirus]]|before=[[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]|after=[[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]|years=297\u2013272 BC}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Demetrius I Poliorcetes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Macedon]]|years=288&ndash;285 BC|with=[[Lysimachus]]}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Antigonus II Gonatas]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Antigonus II Gonatas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Macedon]]|years=274&ndash;272 BC}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MacedonKings}}\n{{Hellenistic rulers}}\n{{Plutarch}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pyrrhus Of Epirus}}\n[[Category:Pyrrhus of Epirus| ]]\n[[Category:272 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:310s BC births]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC Macedonian monarchs]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:4th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient child rulers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Epirotes in Macedon]]\n[[Category:Ancient Epirotes]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek generals]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek military writers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Macedonian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Hellenistic Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Non-dynastic kings of Macedonia (ancient kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Rulers of Ancient Epirus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|King of Epirus}}\n{{About|the Epirote king|other uses|Pyrrhus (disambiguation){{!}}Pyrrhus}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type         = monarch\n| name         = Pyrrhus\n| image        = File:Pyrrhus MAN Napoli Inv6150 n03.jpg\n| image_size   = 250px\n| caption      = Bust of Pyrrhus at the [[National Archaeological Museum of Naples]]\n| succession   = [[King of Epirus]]\n| reign        = 297\u2013272 BC\n| predecessor  = [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]\n| successor    = [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]\n| reign1       = 306\u2013302 BC\n| predecessor1 = [[Alcetas II of Epirus|Alcetas II]]\n| successor1   = [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]\n| succession2  = [[List of ancient Macedonians|King of Macedonia]]\n| reign2       = 274\u2013272 BC\n| predecessor2 = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| successor2   = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| reign3       = 288\u2013285 BC\n| predecessor3 = [[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius I]]\n| successor3   = [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus II]]\n| succession4  = [[List of tyrants of Syracuse|Tyrant of Syracuse]]\n| reign4       = 278\u2013276 BC\n| predecessor4 = [[:it:Tinione|Thinion]] & [[:it:Sosistrato di Agrigento|Sosistratus]]\n| successor4   = [[Hiero II of Syracuse|Hiero II]]\n| house        = [[Aeacidae]]\n| house-type   = Dynasty\n| spouse       = {{plain list|\n* [[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]]\n* [[Lanassa (wife of Pyrrhus)|Lanassa]]\n* [[Bircenna]]}}\n| issue        = {{plain list|\n* [[Olympias II of Epirus|Olympias]]\n* [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]]\n* [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]\n* Helenus\n}}\n| father       = [[Aeacides of Epirus|Aeacides]]\n| mother       = [[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]]\n| birth_date   = c. 319 BC\n| birth_place  = [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]], [[Ancient Greece|Greece]]\n| death_date   = 272 BC (aged about 46)\n| death_place  = [[Argos]], [[Peloponnese]], Greece\n| religion     = [[Greek mythology|Greek Paganism]]\n}}\n\n'''Pyrrhus''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|\u026ar|\u0259|s}}; {{lang-grc|\u03a0\u03cd\u03c1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Pyrrhos''; 319/318\u2013272 BC) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] king and [[wikt:statesman|statesman]] of the [[Hellenistic period]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hackens|1992|p=239}}; {{harvnb|Grant|2010|p=17}}; {{harvnb|Anglin|Hamblin|1993|p=121}}; {{harvnb|Richard|2003|p=139}}; {{harvnb|Sekunda|Northwood|Hook|1995|p=6}}; {{harvnb|Daly|2003|p=4}}; {{harvnb|Greene|2008|p=98}}; {{harvnb|Kishlansky|Geary|O'Brien|2005|p=113}}; {{harvnb|Saylor|2007|p=332}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1967|loc=pp. 340\u2013345}}; Hammond has argued convincingly that the Epirotes were a Greek-speaking people.</ref><ref name=\"Plutarch\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives'', \"[http://classics.mit.edu/Plutarch/pyrrhus.html Pyrrhus]\".</ref><ref name=BritB>{{harvnb|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|2013}}.</ref><ref name=BritA>{{harvnb|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Pyrrhus\")|2013}}.</ref> He was king of the [[List of ancient Greek tribes#Epirus|Greek]] tribe of [[Molossians]],<ref name=BritB/><ref>{{harvnb|Borza|1992|p=62}}.</ref> of the royal Aeacid house,<ref>{{harvnb|Jones|1999|p=45}}; {{harvnb|Chamoux|2003|p=62}}; {{harvnb|American Numismatic Society|1960|p=196}}.</ref> and later he became [[Monarch|king]] ([[John Malalas|Malalas]] also called him [[toparch]]<ref>[https://topostext.org/work/792#8.208 Malalas, Chronography, \u00a7 8.208 ]</ref>) of [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]]. He was one of the strongest opponents of early [[Roman Republic|Rome]]. Several of his victorious battles caused him unacceptably heavy losses, from which the term ''[[Pyrrhic victory]]'' was coined.\n\nPyrrhus became king of Epirus in 306 BC at the age of 13, but was dethroned by [[Cassander]] four years later. He saw action during the [[Wars of the Diadochi]] and regained his throne in 297 BC with the support of [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. During what came to be known as the [[Pyrrhic War]], Pyrrhus fought Rome at the behest of [[Taranto|Tarentum]], scoring costly victories at [[Battle of Heraclea|Heraclea]] and [[Battle of Asculum|Asculum]]. He proceeded to take over [[Sicily]] from [[Carthage]] but was soon driven out, and lost all his gains in Italy after the [[Battle of Beneventum (275 BC)|Battle of Beneventum]] in 275 BC.\n\nPyrrhus seized the Macedonian throne from [[Antigonus II Gonatas]] in 274 BC and [[Pyrrhus' invasion of the Peloponnese|invaded the Peloponnese]] in 272 BC. The Epirote [[Siege of Sparta|assault on Sparta]] was thwarted, however, and Pyrrhus was killed during a street battle at [[Argos]].\n\n==Early life==\nIn c. 319 BC, Pyrrhus was born to prince [[Aeacides of Epirus|Aeacides]] of Epirus,<ref>At Pyrrhus' birth in 319 BC, Aeacides was only a prince and his father, Arrybas, ruled Epirus as a regent to the underaged King Neoptolemus.</ref> and [[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]], a Thessalian noblewoman, the daughter of the Thessalian general [[Menon IV of Pharsalus|Menon]]. Aeacides was a cousin of [[Olympias]], making Pyrrhus a second-cousin-once-removed to [[Alexander the Great]]. He had two sisters: [[Deidamia I of Epirus|Deidamia]] and Troias. In 319/318 BC, Arrybas, Aeacides' father and the regent of Epirus, died leaving Epirus to the joint kings Aeacides and [[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus]]. \n\nAeacides supported Olympias in her fight against [[Cassander]] and marched on Macedon. In 317 BC, when Pyrrhus was only two, Olympias requested Aeacides' support yet again and he marched on Macedon a second time. Many of his soldiers did not like their service and mutinied. Aeacides released these soldiers from his army, but as a result his army was too small to achieve anything. When the mutineers arrived in Epirus they caused a rebellion against their absent king and Aeacides was dethroned. Cassander sent one of his generals, Lyciscus, to act as regent to the still underaged Neoptolemus. Epirus in effect became a puppet kingdom of Cassander. Pyrrhus' family fled north and took refuge with [[King Glaukias|Glaukias]] of the [[Taulantii|Taulantians]], one of the largest [[Illyrians|Illyrian]] tribes.<ref name=BritA/> Pyrrhus was raised by [[Beroea of Epirus|Beroea]], Glaukias' wife, a [[Molossian]] of the [[Aeacidae]] dynasty.<ref name=\"Plutarch\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Wilkes|1992|p=124}}.</ref> Cassander marched against Glaukias, defeated his army and captured [[Apollonia (Illyria)|Apollonia]]. Glaukias had to promise not to act against Cassander, but he refused to give up Pyrrhus and his family.<ref name=JFP12>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=12}}.</ref>\n\nBy 313 BC, Cassander was distracted by his war against [[Antigonus I Monophthalmus|Antigonus Monophthalmus]], one of the most powerful of the [[Diadochi]]. Fearing an invasion from [[Asia Minor]], where Antigonus was building up his forces, he shifted his attention from west to the east. Aeacides took advantage of the situation and returned to Epirus. He appears to have regained popularity and raised a large army. Cassander sent an army under his brother Philip who defeated Aeacides in two battles. Aeacides was wounded in the last battle and died soon after.<ref name=JFP12/>\n\n==First reign==\nIn 307 BC, Glaukias invaded Epirus and put Pyrrhus upon the throne. Pyrrhus was only eleven years old, his guardians would rule in his stead until he came of age.<ref>Justin, ''Epitome'', 17.3.</ref> When he was seventeen he travelled to the court of Glaukias to attend the wedding of one of Glaukias' sons, while he was in Illyria the [[Molossians]] rose in rebellion and drove out Pyrrhus' supporters and placed Neoptolemus back on the throne. This time Glaukias was unable to help him.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=14}}; Glaukias' kingdom was being attacked by pirates.</ref> \n\n==Exile==\nPyrrhus travelled to the [[Peloponnese]] and served his brother-in-law [[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius Poliorcetes]] who had married his sister Deidamia, and who was campaigning against Cassander in southern Greece.\n\n===The Battle of Ipsus===\n{{main|Battle of Ipsus}}\nIn 302 BC, Demetrius took his army to Asia Minor to support his father Antigonus Monophthalmus. Pyrrhus impressed Antigonus for he is reputed to have said that Pyrrhus would become the greatest general of his time, if he lived long enough.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=15}}.</ref>\n\nAntigonus had grown too powerful and the other successors, [[Seleucus I Nicator|Seleucus]], [[Lysimachus]], [[Ptolemy I Soter|Ptolemy]] and [[Cassander]], had united against him. Lysimachus and Seleucus, reinforced by two of Cassander's armies, had concentrated their forces in Asia Minor and marched on Antigonus. Both armies met at [[Ipsus]] in [[Phrygia]]. The Battle of Ipsus was the largest and most important battle of the [[Wars of the Diadochi|Wars of the Successors]]. Pyrrhus probably fought with Demetrius on the right wing, a place of honour, and made a brilliant display of valour among the combatants. Unfortunately for Antigonus, he lost both the battle and his life. Demetrius, victorious on his wing, managed to escape with 9,000 men. Pyrrhus, still with Demetrius, continued to serve his brother-in-law who started rebuilding his father's empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=14\u201317}}.</ref>\n\n===Ptolemy===\nIn 298 BC, Pyrrhus was taken hostage to Alexandria, under the terms of a peace treaty made between Demetrius and [[Ptolemy I Soter]]. There, he married Ptolemy I's stepdaughter [[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]] (a daughter of [[Berenice I of Egypt]] from her first husband [[Philip (first husband of Berenice I of Egypt)|Philip]]\u2014respectively, Ptolemy I's wife and a Macedonian noble). In 297 BC, Cassander died and Ptolemy, always looking for allies, decided to help restore Pyrrhus to his kingdom. He provided Pyrrhus with men and funds and sent him back to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=18}}.</ref>\n\n==Second reign==\nPyrrhus returned to Epirus at the head of an army, but not willing to fight a civil war he agreed to rule Epirus together with Neoptolemus. Soon both kings started to plot against one another. Pyrrhus was informed of a plot against his life and decided to strike first. He invited his fellow king to a dinner and had him murdered. The act does not appear to be unpopular as Epirus' nobility seem to have been devoted to him.<ref>Plutarch. ''Life of Pyrrhus'', 5.</ref> \n\nIn 295 BC, Pyrrhus transferred the capital of his kingdom to [[Arta, Greece|Ambracia]]. In 292 BC, he went to war against his former ally and brother-in-law Demetrius, he invaded [[Thessaly]] while Demetrius was [[Siege of Thebes (292-291 BC)|besieging Thebes]]. Demetrius responded immediately, he left the siege to his son [[Antigonus Gonatas]] and marched back north at the head of a large army.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=32}}; Demetrius commanded the full might of the Macedonian army which at that particular time was much larger than the army of Epirus.</ref> Pyrrhus, outnumbered, withdrew to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=32}}.</ref>\n\nWhile he was back in Epirus, Pyrrhus suffered another setback. His second wife Lannasa, daughter of [[Agathocles of Syracuse|Agathocles]] the self proclaimed king of [[Sicily]], deserted him. She claimed that she, a daughter of a Greek king, could no longer bare to share her home with barbarian women. She fled to [[Corcyra]], her dowry, and offered it and herself to Demetrius. He accepted, sailed to the island and took possession of both Corcyra and Lannasa. After returning to his army in mainland Greece, Demetrius planned to invade Epirus. In 289 BC, he invaded Pyrrhus' allies the [[Aetolian League|Aetolians]], hoping to neutralize them before he invaded Epirus. The Aetolians refused battle and retreated into the hills. After ransacking their countryside, Demetrius left a strong force under his best general Pantauchus in Aetolia and marched on Epirus. Meanwhile, Pyrrhus had raised his army and was marching to his allies rescue. The two armies, on different roads, passed one another and Demetrius started plundering Epirus while Pyrrhus met Pantauchus in battle.\n\nPyrrhus had the bulk of the army of Epirus with him, probably 20,000-25,000 men, while Pantauchus commanded but a detachment of Demetrius' army consisting of around 11,000 men. The fighting was heavy, and according to the sources Pantauchus and Pyrrhus sought out one another. Pantauchus challenged Pyrrhus to individual combat, Pyrrhus accepted. After hurling spears at each other they fought it out with swords. Pyrrhus was wounded, but in return wounded his opponent twice, in the thigh and in the neck. Pantauchus' bodyguards had to carry him away. Emboldened by their king's victory the Epirots resumed their attack and broke Pantauchus' army, and took 5,000 prisoners. The army then honoured Pyrrhus by bestowing the surname of 'Eagle' upon him. Demetrius, upon hearing of Pyrrhus' victory, marched back to Macedon. Pyrrhus released his prisoners and marched back to Epirus.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=33\u201334}}.</ref>\n \nIn 289 BC, Pyrrhus, learning that Demetrius was dangerously ill, invaded Macedonia. His original intention was merely to raid and pillage, but with Demetrius unable to lead his forces he met almost no opposition. Pyrrhus penetrated as far as the old Macedonian capital of Aegae before Demetrius was well enough to take the field. Since Demetrius commanded a superior force Pyrrhus had no choice but to retreat.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=34}}.</ref>\n\nDemetrius, just as restless as Pyrrhus, planned to invade Asia and reclaim his father's old domains. He first made peace with Pyrrhus granting him his holdings in Macedonia while holding on to Corcyra and Leucas, then he started to raise a vast army and a huge fleet.<ref>Reputedly raising 110,000 soldiers and 500 ships.</ref> Faced with this threat, the other Diadochi, Lysimachus, Ptolemy and Seleucus, allied against him. The three kings sent embassies to Pyrrhus trying to win him over to their side or at least get him to remain neutral. If the allies won and Pyrrhus remained neutral he would gain nothing. If on the other hand Demetrius would be victorious he could overwhelm Pyrrhus at any time in the future. Pyrrhus personal enmity against Demetrius might have played an additional role in his decision to join the allies.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=34\u201335}}.</ref>\n\nIn 288 BC, the allied kings began their campaigns against Demetrius. Ptolemy sailed against Demetrius' Greek allies with a large fleet. Lysimachus invaded upper Macedonia from Thrace. Pyrrhus waited untill Demetrius had marched against Lysimachus and then invaded southern Macedonia. Demetrius must have thought Pyrrhus would not renege on his treaty for western and southern Macedonia fell without opposition. Meanwhile, Demetrius had won a victory over Lysimachus near [[Amphipolis]]. When the Macedonian army heard their homeland was being overrun by Pyrrhus they turned on Demetrius. They were fed up with his autocratic rule and grandiose plans and refused to advance any further. Demetrius then led his army against Pyrrhus, probably hoping his Macedonians would be more willing to fight a foreign invader than Lysimachus, a veteran of Alexander. Unfortunately for Demetrius, his troops were so fed up with him they deserted to Pyrrhus and he had to flee. Lysimachus was soon joined by Pyrrhus and they decided to share rulership over Macedonia.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=35\u201336}}.</ref>\n\nDemetrius gathered a new army in Greece and besieged Athens, which had rebelled against the puppet government he had installed. The Athenians called on Pyrrhus for assistance and he marched against Demetrius once more. This caused Demetrius to raise the siege. The Athenians thanked Pyrrhus, they erected a bust to him and allowed him into the city for the celebrations. However, they did not allow his army to enter the city, probably fearing Pyrrhus would install a garrison and make himself overlord of Athens. Pyrrhus made the most of the situation and advised the Athenians never to let a king enter their city again.<ref name=JFP37>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=37}}.</ref>\n\nPyrrhus and Demetrius made peace once more but, like all previous agreements, it did not last. When Demetrius, in 286 BC, invaded Asia, to attack Lysimachus' Asian domains, Lysimachus requested Pyrrhus invade Thessaly and from there attack Demetrius' garrisons in Greece. Pyrrhus agreed, probably to keep his fractious Macedonian troops busy and less likely to rebel and also to gain an easy victory over the weakened Antigonids.<ref>Plutarch. ''Pyrrhus'', 12; Plutarch. ''Demetrius'', 41.</ref> He quickly defeated [[Antigonus Gonatas]], Demetrius' son, who ceded Thessaly to him in order to make peace. Pyrrhus' Greek Empire was now at its zenith, he ruled an enlarged Epirus, half of Macedonia and Thessaly.<ref name=JFP37/> \n\nIn 285 BC, Demetrius was defeated by Seleucus. This freed the hands of Lysimachus who decided to get rid of his co-ruler in Macedonia. He first isolated Pyrrhus from his traditional ally the Ptolemies, by marrying [[Arsinoe II|Arsinoe]], the sister of [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus|Ptolemy II]]. He also made a large donation to the [[Aetolians]], Pyrrhus' main allies in Greece. Pyrrhus felt threatened enough to make an alliance with Antigonus Gonatas. In 284 BC, Lysimachus invaded Pyrrhus' half of Macedonia with a huge army.<ref>In 301 BC, at the Battle of Ipsus, Lysimachus had fielded 40,000 troops. Since then he had acquired half of Macedonia and western Asia Minor. With these combined assets his army could have numbered over 70,000 troops. Pyrrhus commanded 40,000 troops at best.</ref> Unable to stand against Lysimachus' superior army Pyrrhus retreated and linked up with Antigonus Gonatas. Lysimachus started a propaganda campaign in which he appealed to the patriotism of the Macedonians serving Pyrrhus. He reminded them that Pyrrhus was in fact a foreign king while he himself was a true Macedonian. The campaign was successful. With his Macedonian troops turning against him Pyrrhus had no other choice but to withdraw to Epirus. Lysimachus invaded an plundered Epirus the following year. Pyrrhus did not oppose Lysimachus for he was probably fighting a war in Illyria to the north. According to Pausanius, \"Pyrrhus was roaming around as usual\".<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=37\u201339}}; {{harvnb|Greenwalt|2010|p=298: \"From 288 until 284, Pyrrhus and Lysimachus shared the rule of Macedonia until the latter drove the former back to Epirus (Plut., ''Pyrrhus'' 7\u201312).\"}}; Pausanius. ''Guide to Greece'', 1.7.</ref>\n\n==Struggle with Rome==\n{{Main|Pyrrhic War|}}\n[[Image:Pyrrhic War Italy en.svg|thumb|left|Routes taken against Rome in the [[Pyrrhic War]] (280\u2013275 BC).]]\n[[Image:Map of ancient Epirus and environs (English).svg|thumb|Tribes of Epirus in antiquity.]]\n[[File:Pyrrhus and his Elephants.gif|thumb|upright|Pyrrhus and his elephants.]]\n\nThe Greek city of [[Taranto|Tarentum]], in [[Mezzogiorno|southern Italy]], fell out with [[Roman Republic|Rome]] due to a violation of an old treaty that specified Rome was not to send warships into the [[Tarentine Gulf]].<ref>{{harvnb|Hackens|1992|loc=pp. 20-21: \"When, however, a Roman fleet sailed into the Tarentine Gulf (perhaps in order to place a garrison in Thurii) and thereby violated the terms of a treaty probably made at the time of Cleomynus, Tarentum responded swiftly \u2026 \"}}</ref> In 282 BC, the Romans installed garrisons in the Greek cities of [[Thurii]] (on the western end of the Tarentine Gulf), [[Locri]], and [[Rhegium]], and sent warships to Thurii. Although this was designed as a measure against the Italian peoples of [[Lucanians|Lucania]], the Tarentines grew nervous and attacked the Romans in Thurii, driving the Roman garrison from the city and sinking several Roman warships. Tarentum was now faced with a Roman attack and certain defeat, unless they could enlist the aid of greater powers. Rome had already made itself into a major power, and was poised to subdue all the Greek cities in [[Magna Graecia]]. The Tarentines asked Pyrrhus to lead their war against the Romans.<ref name=BritA/><ref name=encarta2008>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Pyrrhus|encyclopedia=Encarta|publisher=Microsoft Corporation|year=2008}}</ref> Pyrrhus was encouraged to aid the Tarentines by the [[Oracle of Delphi]]. He recognized the possibility of carving out an empire for himself in [[Italy]]. He made an alliance with [[Ptolemy Keraunos]], King of [[Macedon]] and his most powerful neighbor, and arrived in Italy in 280 BC.\n\nPyrrhus entered Italy with an army consisting of 20,000 [[infantry]], 3,000 [[cavalry]], 2,000 [[archery|archers]], 500 [[sling (weapon)|slingers]], and 20 [[war elephant]]s in a bid to subdue the Romans.<ref name=BritA/> The elephants had been loaned to him by [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus]], who had also promised 9,000 soldiers and a further 50 elephants to defend Epirus while Pyrrhus and his army were away.\n\nDue to his superior cavalry, his elephants and his deadly [[macedonian phalanx|phalanx infantry]], he defeated the Romans, led by [[Consul]] [[Publius Valerius Laevinus]], in the [[Battle of Heraclea]] in 280 BC,<ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/History-of-Liberty-the-Ancient-Romans-Volume-2/105987/37 \"History of Liberty: The Ancient Romans\" (1853), p. 6.]</ref> in the Roman province of [[Lucania]]. There are conflicting sources about casualties. [[Hieronymus of Cardia]] reports the Romans lost about 7,000 while Pyrrhus lost 3,000 soldiers, including many of his best; Dionysius gives a bloodier view of 15,000 Roman dead and 13,000 Epirot.<ref name=\"Plutarch17.4\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0060%3Achapter%3D17%3Asection%3D4 17.4].</ref> Several tribes, including the [[Lucanians]], [[Bruttii]], [[Messapians]], and the Greek cities of [[Crotone|Croton]] and [[Locri]], joined Pyrrhus. He then offered the Romans a peace treaty which was eventually rejected. Pyrrhus tried to wrest [[Campania]] from the Romans, but was twarted in this by the reinforced army of Laevinus. He then boldly marched on Rome itself, but found its defences too formidable. Meanwhile, the Romans had made peace with the Etruscans and had recalled [[Tiberius Coruncanius]], the other consul, who was marching his army southwards from [[Etruria]] towards Rome. Pyrrhus now faced three armies; the garrison of Rome, Laevinus from the south and Curuncanius from the north. Not wanting to be caught between three armies Pyrrhus withdrew to Tarentum, where he wintered his troops.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=75\u201376}}.</ref>\n\nWhen Pyrrhus invaded [[Apulia]] (279 BC), the two armies met in the [[Battle of Asculum]], where Pyrrhus won a costly victory.<ref name=encarta2008/> The consul [[Publius Decius Mus (279 BC)|Publius Decius Mus]] was the Roman commander, and while his able force was ultimately defeated, they almost managed to break the back of Pyrrhus' Epirot army, which guaranteed the security of the city itself. In the end, the Romans lost 6,000 men and Pyrrhus 3,500 including many officers.<ref name=BritA/> Pyrrhus later famously commented on his victory at Asculum, stating, \"If we are victorious in one more battle with the Romans, we shall be utterly ruined\".<ref name=\"Plutarch21.9\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Pyrrhus*.html#21 21.9].</ref> It is from reports of this semi-legendary event that the term [[Pyrrhic victory]] originates.\n\n==Ruler of Sicily==\nIn 278 BC, Pyrrhus received two offers simultaneously. The Greek cities in [[Sicily]] asked him to come and drive out [[Carthage]], which along with Rome was one of the two great powers of the Western [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]]. At the same time, the [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonians]], whose King [[Ptolemy Keraunos]] had been killed by invading [[Gauls]], asked Pyrrhus to ascend the throne of Macedon. Pyrrhus decided that Sicily offered him a greater opportunity, and transferred his army there.<ref name=BritA/>\n\nSoon after landing in Sicily, he lifted the Carthaginian [[Siege of Syracuse (278 BC)|siege of Syracuse]] in the same year. Pyrrhus was proclaimed king of Sicily. He was already making plans for his son Helenus to inherit the kingdom of Sicily and his other son Alexander to be given Italy. In 277 BC, Pyrrhus captured [[Eryx (Sicily)|Eryx]], the strongest Carthaginian fortress in Sicily. This prompted the rest of the Carthaginian-controlled cities to defect to Pyrrhus.\n\nIn 276 BC, Pyrrhus negotiated with the Carthaginians. Although they were inclined to come to terms with Pyrrhus, supply him money and send him ships once friendly relations were established, he demanded that Carthage abandon all of Sicily and make the Libyan Sea a boundary between themselves and the Greeks. The Greek cities of Sicily opposed making peace with Carthage because the Carthaginians still controlled the powerful fortress of [[Lilybaeum]], on the western end of the island. Pyrrhus eventually gave in to their proposals and broke off the peace negotiations. Pyrrhus' army then began [[Siege of Lilybaeum|besieging Lilybaeum]]. For two months he launched unsuccessful assaults on the city, until finally he realized he could not mount an effective siege without blockading it from the sea as well. Pyrrhus then requested manpower and money from the Sicilians in order to construct a powerful fleet. When the Sicilians became unhappy about these contributions he had to resort to compulsory contributions and force to keep them in line. These measures culminated in him proclaiming a military dictatorship of Sicily and installing military garrisons in Sicilian cities.<ref>{{harvnb|Garouphalias|1979|pp=97\u2013108}}.</ref>\n\nThese actions were deeply unpopular and soon Sicilian opinion became inflamed against him. Pyrrhus had so alienated the Sicilian Greeks that they were willing to make common cause with the Carthaginians. The Carthaginians took heart from this and sent another army against him. This army was promptly defeated. In spite of this victory, Sicily continued to grow increasingly hostile to Pyrrhus, who began to consider abandoning Sicily. At this point, Samnite and Tarentine envoys reached Pyrrhus and informed him that of all the Greek cities in Italy, only Tarentum had not been conquered by Rome. Pyrrhus made his decision and departed from Sicily. As his ship left the island, he turned and, foreshadowing the [[Punic Wars]], said to his companions: \"What a wrestling ground we are leaving, my friends, for the Carthaginians and the Romans.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Garouphalias|1979|pp=109\u2013112}}.</ref><ref>Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives: Pyrrhus'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0060%3Achapter%3D23%3Asection%3D6 23.6].</ref> While his army was being transported by ship to mainland Italy, Pyrrhus' navy was destroyed by the Carthaginians at the [[Battle of the Strait of Messina]], with 98 warships sunk or disabled out of 110.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"105px\">\nFile:Pyros.jpg|Coin of Pyrrhus minted at [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], 278 BC. Obverse: Veiled head of [[Phthia of Epirus|Phtia]] with oak wreath, caption \u03a6\u0398\u0399\u0391\u03a3 (of Phtia). Reverse: [[Thunderbolt]], \u0392\u0391\u03a3\u0399\u039b\u0395\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0\u03a5\u03a1\u03a1\u039f\u03a5 (of King Pyrrhus).\nFile:Pyrrhos KING of EPEIROS 297 272 BC.jpg|Pyrrhos, King of Epeiros, 297\u201372 BC. Head of Zeus in wreath of oak / Demeter seated, holding long sceptre and her veil; caption \u0392\u0391\u03a3\u0399\u039b\u0395\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0\u03a5\u03a1\u03a1\u039f\u03a5 (of king Pyrrhus).\nFile:Pyrrhus Kingdom of Epirus.JPG|Coin of Pyrrhus, [[Epirus (ancient state)|Kingdom of Epirus]] Head of Kore left, wreathed with grain, long torch behind / Athena Alkis advancing left, brandishing spear in right hand & holding shield on left arm, star before face, thunderbolt in left field, E in right field; inscription BA\u03a3I\u039bE\u03a9\u03a3 \u03a0Y\u03a1\u03a1OY (of King Pyrrhus).\n</gallery>\n\n==Retreat from Italy==\nWhile Pyrrhus had been campaigning against the Carthaginians, the Romans had rebuilt their army by calling up thousands of fresh [[Army recruit|recruits]]. When Pyrrhus returned from Sicily, he found himself vastly outnumbered against a superior Roman army under [[Manius Curius Dentatus]]. After the inconclusive [[Battle of Beneventum (275 BC)|Battle of Beneventum]] in 275 BC, Pyrrhus decided to end his campaign in Italy and return to Epirus which resulted in the loss of essentially all the gains he had made in Italy. The city of Tarentum remained under the dominion of the Epirotes.\n\n==Last wars and death==\n{{Main|Siege of Sparta|}}\n[[File:The-Siege-Of-Sparta-By-Pyrrhus-319-272-Bc-1799-1800.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Siege of Sparta]], by [[Fran\u00e7ois Topino-Lebrun]]]]\n\nHis western campaign had taken a heavy toll on his army as well as his treasury. Despite (or perhaps because of) this, Pyrrhus went to war yet again.<ref>The easiest way for a king to raise funds was to invade his neighbours.</ref> The realm of his rival king [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonus Gonatas]] of Macedon was the most obvious target. Pyrrhus raised an army from his Epirote garrisons, Gallic mercenaries and the troops he had brought back from Italy and marched east into Macedon. He won an easy victory at the [[Battle of the Aous (274 BC)|Battle of the Aous]] and took most of Macedon.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|pp=125\u2013128}}; Plutarch. ''Life of Pyrrhus'', 26.</ref>\n\nAntigonus managed to hold on to a number of coastal cities.<ref>He had inherited a powerful navy from his father, Demetrius.</ref> He then waited for an opportunity to reclaim his kingdom while Pyrrhus was already looking for another war to fight. Furthermore Pyrrhus made himself very unpopular in Macedon by allowing his Gauls to plunder the tombs of the Macedonian kings at Aegae.<ref>{{harvnb|Champion|2009|p=128}}.</ref> \n\nIn 272 BC, [[Cleonymus of Sparta|Cleonymus]], a [[Sparta]]n of royal blood who was hated among fellow Spartans, asked Pyrrhus to attack Sparta and place him in power. Pyrrhus agreed to the plan, intending to win control of the [[Peloponnese]] for himself, but unexpected strong resistance thwarted his [[Siege of Sparta|assault on Sparta]]. On the retreat he lost his firstborn son [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]], who had been in command of the rearguard.\n\nPyrrhus had little time to mourn, as he was immediately offered an opportunity to intervene in a civic dispute in [[Pyrrhus'_invasion_of_the_Peloponnese#Battle_of_Argos|Argos]]. Since Antigonus Gonatas was approaching too, he hastened to enter the city with his army by stealth, only to find the place crowded with hostile troops. During the confused [[Battle of Argos]] in the narrow city streets, Pyrrhus was trapped.  While he was fighting an Argive soldier, the soldier's old mother, who was watching from a rooftop, threw a tile which knocked him from his horse and broke part of his spine, paralyzing him.  Whether he was alive or not after the blow is unknown, but his death was assured when a Macedonian soldier named Zopyrus, though frightened by the look on the face of the unconscious king, hesitantly and ineptly beheaded his motionless body. This story is later recounted by Plutarch in his ''Life of Pyrrhus.'' \n\nAntigonus had him cremated with all honours and sent his surviving son Helenus back to Epirus. That same year, upon hearing the news of Pyrrhus's death, the Tarentinians surrendered to Rome.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:20140415 ioannina524.JPG|upright=0.5|thumb|A statue of Pyrrhus in [[Ioannina]], [[Greece]].]]\n\nIn his ''Life of Pyrrhus'', [[Plutarch]] records that [[Hannibal]] ranked him as the greatest commander the world had ever seen,<ref name = \"Plutarch\"/> though in the ''Life of Titus Quinctius Flamininus'', Plutarch writes that Hannibal placed him second after [[Alexander the Great]]. This latter account is also given by [[Appian]].<ref name=\"Appian\">Appian. ''History of the Syrian Wars'', [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_syriaca_02.html \u00a710] and [https://www.livius.org/ap-ark/appian/appian_syriaca_03.html \u00a711].</ref> While he was a mercurial and often restless leader, and not always a wise king, he was considered one of the greatest military commanders of his time. \n\nPyrrhus was known for his benevolence. As a general, Pyrrhus's greatest political weaknesses were his failures to maintain focus and to maintain a strong treasury at home (many of his soldiers were costly mercenaries). \n\nHis name is famous for the term \"[[Pyrrhic victory]]\" which refers to an exchange at the Battle of Asculum. In response to congratulations for winning a costly victory over the Romans, he is reported to have said: \"If we are victorious in one more battle with the Romans, we shall be utterly ruined\".<ref name=\"Plutarch21.9\" />\n\nPyrrhus and his campaign in Italy was effectively the only chance for Greece to check the advance of Rome towards domination of the Mediterranean world. Rather than banding together, the various Hellenistic powers continued to quarrel among themselves, sapping the financial and military strength of Greece and to a lesser extent, Macedon and the greater Hellenistic world. By 197 BC, Macedonia and many southern Greek city-states became Roman client states; in 188 BC, the [[Seleucid Empire]] was forced to cede most of [[Asia Minor]] to Rome's ally [[Pergamon]] (Pergamum). Rome inherited that state, and most of Asia Minor in 133 BC. Total Roman domination over Greece proper was marked by the [[Battle of Corinth (146 BC)|destruction of Corinth]] in 146 BC; Greece then formed an integral part of the Roman world leading into the [[Byzantine]] period.\n\nPyrrhus wrote memoirs and several books on the art of war. These have since been lost, although, according to Plutarch, Hannibal was influenced by them,<ref name=\"Plutarch\"/> and they received praise from [[Cicero]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tinsley|2006|p=211}}.</ref>\n\nPyrrhus was married five times: his first wife Antigone bore him a daughter called [[Olympias II of Epirus|Olympias]] and a son named [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]] in honour of her [[Ptolemy I Soter|stepfather]]. She died in 295 BC, possibly in childbirth, since that was the same year her son was born.<ref name=\"harvnb|Bennett|2010\">{{harvnb|Bennett|2010}}.</ref> His second wife was [[Lanassa (wife of Pyrrhus)|Lanassa]], daughter of King [[Agathocles of Syracuse]] (r. 317\u2013289 BC), whom he married in about 295 BC; the couple had two sons, [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander]]<ref name=\"harvnb|Bennett|2010\"/> and Helenus; Lanassa left Pyrrhus. His third wife was the daughter of [[Audoleon]], King of [[Paeonia (kingdom)|Paeonia]]; his fourth wife was the Illyrian princess [[Bircenna]], who was the daughter of King [[Bardylis II]] (r. c. 295\u2013290 BC); and his fifth wife was the daughter of [[Ptolemy Keraunos]], whom he married in 281/280 BC. Portraits of Pyrrhus as have come down to us do not necessarily reflect his likeness.<ref>{{harvnb|Winkes|1995|pp=175\u2013188}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=American Numismatic Society|title=Numismatic Literature, Issues 50-57|publisher=American Numismatic Society|year=1960|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZGkvAQAAIAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Anglin|first1=Jay Pascal|last2=Hamblin|first2=William James|title=HarperCollins College Outline World History to 1648|location=New York, NY|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993|isbn=0-06-467123-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t4luVpw3NOIC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Chris|title=Antigone (Egyptian Royal Genealogy - The Ptolemaic Dynasty)|publisher=Tyndale House|url=http://www.tyndalehouse.com/egypt/ptolemies/antigone_fr.htm|year=2010|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Borza|first=Eugene N.|title=In the Shadow of Olympus: The Emergence of Macedon (Revised Edition)|location=Princeton, NJ|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1992|isbn=0-691-00880-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=614pd07OtfQC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Champion|first=Jeff|title=Pyrrhus of Epirus|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire|publisher=Pen & Sword Books Limited|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84468-282-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6YivDwAAQBAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Chamoux|first=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Hellenistic Civilization|location=Oxford, UK|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|year=2003|isbn=0-631-22242-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nafU9ADpCwcC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Daly|first=Gregory|title=Cannae: The Experience of Battle in the Second Punic War|location=New York, NY and London, UK|publisher=Routledge (Taylor & Francis)|year=2003|isbn=0-203-98750-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XzkY6voGtHgC|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/190156/Epirus|title=Epirus|